\pard\plain \ltrch\loch \f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 ###1 }
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 Avoid roller coaster of emotions above all things - this.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 So if you ever feel this way, tell me. If I feel this way I am going to tell you. Probably this is directed my fault, but maybe im saying that because im always trying to ascribe fault to me. }
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 It\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s not that they don\u8217\'92t want love, its that love reminds them of dependency, vulnerability, and the helplessness they felt long ago.}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 So when you try to love them deeply, they didn\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92t see it as affection, they saw it as a threat. The more you try to hold them, the more they needed to pull away.}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 They move on to someone who is easier. Someone who doesn\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92t ask deep questions, someone who doesnt\u8217\'92 challenge their walls. This new person might seem perfect on the surface, calm, detached, maybe even emotionally unavailable themselves. But that\u8217\'92s the key. Avoidants end up with people who don\u8217\'92t require much. They often choose partners who mirror their own avoidance, emotionally cold, or secretly anxious but too afraid to show it. It\u8217\'92s not love that draws them in, its safety through distance. This is why so many avoidants end up in relationships that look stable from the outside, but are emotionally dead on the inside. There\u8217\'92s no chaos, no deep connection, no growth. Just routine.}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 The avoidant feel safe because they\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92re not being asked to show their heart. They can exist not exposed. But over time that same safety turnes into emptiness. Because deep down they crave what they fear most, real intimacy.}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 Exhausting cycle of craving closeness, but fearing it.}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 Some avoidants end up with anxious partners. The kind who chase, please, and overgive. It feels like a match made in dysfunction. The anxious partner feeds the avoidants need for distance, the avoidant feeds the anxious\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92 needs for validation. It\u8217\'92s an emotional dance where both receive just enough to stay hooked, but never enough to feel whole.}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 The anxious partner thinks, if I just love them harder, they\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92ll open up. The avoidant thinks, if I can keep them chasing, ill never have to face my fear of intimacy. And so they both mistake tension for connection.}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 Emotional distance is not power. It is protection. Protection that is permanent, is a prison. When they realize this, they no longer chase easy relationships.  They start to crave authenticity. They want to feel safe and seen. That\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s when they can finally love deeply. }
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 They fall in love with someone who doesn\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92t chase them. Because love isn\u8217\'92t about begging for crumbs. It\u8217\'92s about creating emotional safety that allows both people to unfold, not hide.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 \line Calm, grounded, patient but not self-sacrificing.}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 A quiet companionship with someone who doesn\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92t trigger their fears, but doesn\u8217\'92t awaken their heart.}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 They\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92re not seeking a soulmate, they\u8217\'92re seeking a relief from the intensity of their own emotions.}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 Fear losing control of themselves in love. So they build relationships where they never have to risk.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 Love without vulnerability. Affection without depth. Commitment without surrender.}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 \hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 }
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 Avoidant prioritizes self protection over relationship connection}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 But you have to have a healthy balance of both.}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 When presented with an opportunity to expose themselves emotionally, they retract.}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 Attracts savior men - you can feel that she is stuck in the tower, that she wants something that she is not getting. She wants intimacy, desire, to be loved, to be known and understood. She craves those things. Creates this deep spark, this yearning, of, I will save her from herself.}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 When that happens, men get stuck in the dance with her.}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 Also attracts guys who fill up more than their share of emotional space. They fill the void with their own emotions. So he overtalks, overcommunicates, becomes more anxious than he normally would be in other relationships. Starts to chase her and pursue her, and all that does is it reinforces the avoidant\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s behavior of, I need to protect myself from you.}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 So you need to step away. She needs to save herself by choosing a relationship and connection over self protection.}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 The healing happens in a relationship. We are hurt in a relationship, it takes a relationship to heal it.}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 Most avoidant women dont believe that anyone wants to learn about their inner experience. Other people just generally don\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92t care about who I am, and so ill never be understood.}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 1.) Ladies, communicate your needs.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 \tab -all the things that the other person is going to reject you for, or punish you for, those are things which need to be shared.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 \tab -start small, I would like to go on a date night}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 \tab -work up to big needs}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 If I ask, how was yoru day, and they say \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8216\'91fine\u8217\'92 they need to choose emotional connection.}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 2.) }
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 A letter about what the avoidant seeks in a relationship.}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 I need ask to what extent she\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s healed from avoidance, and to what extent she needs me to help.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 There was never a, what I need from you, moment.}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 Lean into conflict, and not away}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 Conditioned to believe that conflict is dangerous useless, unproductive, etc. But there\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s no change without confrontation.}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 Did not learn how to do conflict effectively \hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0  she mentioned this.  This could be a first.}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 1.) do not wait more than 24 hours before reconnection. Healthy conflict is one that is not left to linger. Lean into the repair.}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 2.) for me, create more space for her emotions. Take up more space of emotional expression, and talk about their internal experience a lot more. Create more specific opportunities for her to share her internal reality, her experience.}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 3.) move from questions to statements. Instead of asking, do you want to tell me about your day, say, \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93tell me about your day.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 Be firm in saying, \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93I want to hear about it\u8221\'94.}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 Give thanks instead of criticism. Never say, \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93your not opening up\u8221\'94, its, \u8220\'93thanks for opening up here.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 Thank her and give gratitude for the breadcumbs. Her internal reality is welcome in your relationship.}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 Clearly communicate your expectations, gives her an opportunity to do the same.}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 Asking to have more regular texting or dates}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 With avoidants its classic that they show up in your life whenever its convenient for their schedule, and its few and far in between.  Anytime you ask for closes it can trigger response taht I am about to describe}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 The second thing is when some sort of disconnection has happened with conflict or arguments, and the two of you have had time to reconnect, and youre hoping for some kind of mutual accountability for the disconnection in the first place. Both of these can cause what I call the flip: The flip is when an avoidant acts like you\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92re crazy for wanting normal connection.}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 You\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92re crazy, your abnormal, but no, you\u8217\'92re just wanting a healthy normal connection.}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 Avoidants stay in this position because it is a power position. They have a lot of control, and a lot of security in this place.}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 Avoidants have one thing they rely on to feel safe: emotional availability without commitment.}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 I see you, I accept you, I choose myself.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 Avoidant expects either compliance or chaos, never quiet self respect. They either expect you to stay and suffer silently, or leave loudly.}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 Courage is not the absence of fear, but the judgement that something else is more important.}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 Motivate yourself by what you want in life; positive goals}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 Start by noticing when you are catastrophising:}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 Challenge those thoughts}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 SO eager to get out of this moment.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 \line Why?}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 WHat if this is the best feeling any human being has ever had, and I\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92m here feeling it, but then drop it because I\u8217\'92m worried about income.}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 Keep reading wives loving their husbands to death, but worried about their mental health. Like, what!? Never wanted to be that guy where there is a girl right there and looks past it. Not going to be that guy.}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 A lot of late nights realizing patterns of thought, and fears. }
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 CODEPENDENCY:}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 2 roles - might occupy one, or both at different points, depends on the other individual that you\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92re dating.}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 The  giver - the person who is trying to find belonging and security, worth, value, confidence, connection, intimacy, by disregarding their own wants and needs, and over prioritizing the other person.}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 The taker - the person who is on the receiving end of that. Receiving needs being overly prioritizing, abundance of praise or affection, having things done for them. }
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 The hallmark of a codependent relationship is that you are upset with the other person\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s role. If you are the giver, and you are constantly deprioritizing your own needs your own wants, you villainize them for always being selfish or bad. The main piece to getting out of this is to realize that the giver and taker are amoral, neither good nor bad. That moralizing is a part of what keeps couples in codependent dances, because generally what happens is that the taker will take on an entitled attidude; \u8220\'93you should be doing this for me, you should be saying yes to me, you should be taking care of this for me, how come you\u8217\'92re not meeting my expectations.\u8221\'94 And the giver will take on this sort of victim mentality of \u8216\'91how come I have to take care of everything for you, why wont you take care of my, why wont you prioritize my needs\u8217\'92, and so the giver takes on a sacrificial lamb martyr attitude, and sees the taker as the oppressor. }
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 What causes codependency?}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 Byproduct of childhood}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 Men who with emotional absent parents tend to chase emotionally absent women. Can have a sexual charge to it. Trying to prove, inadvertently, to the woman that we are pursuing, that we are worthy of their attention. \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93If I can get you, I can disprove the pain I\u8217\'92ve been carrying around since childhood.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 Emotional abuse as a child - you will have developed an overprioritization of trying to stay very close to other people\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s needs and wants and a hypervigilance of catering to other people as a protective strategy. As a child became obsessed with thinking about what is going to keep me safe and out of trouble, and out of harms way. Will try to comform behavior, identity, and choices to what they think is going to keep them out of abuse, out of harms way. \hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0  produces behaviors in you that are hypervigiliant into what does she need, what is she thinking, what is she expecting, how can I cater to her needs, how can I be sure that she is okay, above and beyond me, so that I am safe.}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 This is the skeleton in the closet that is fueling codependency in the relationship. If you\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92ve never dealt with that trauma, it is very unlikely that you will shift out of that codependent behavior, until you address the abuse/trauma. They are unequivocally interconnected.}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1  If you were abused, a couple things happen.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 1.) very common for it to get personalized; will likely have felt or thought that the abuse was happening because there was something inherently wrong with you. Become a man who feels like all of the problems taht unfold in the relationship are your fault. This puts you in the role of constantly being in the wrong. May even cause you to actively self sabatoge, to be the person who is in the wrong, person who is constantly wrecking the intimacy, damaging communication, or creating disconnection. I\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92m always the one that is creating problems in the relationship.}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 3.) Emotionally unavailable parent; some people say this is trauma; when you\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92ve had an emotionally unavailable parent; }
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 Almost always, these men took it to mean there was something fundamentally flawed within them. What bubbles up internally is: \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93They must not be giving me attention because there\u8217\'92s something wrong with me\u8221\'94 So, these men chase their partners. Chasing, pursuing women who are unavailable, hot and cold, leave them on read.}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 /neglect, avoidance, abandonment}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 Overindex the parents needs, constantly trying to figure out how to get affection. Becomes an adult and trying to problem solve. Constantly peppering her with those types of questions, \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93what does she need, what is she feeling, are you okay?\u8221\'94 Constantly asking her that two or three times a day.\line Those are the boy in you constantly trying to figure out why wont this parent give me some attention.}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 \line 4) caretaker as a child for caregiver; can become caretaker as an adult, or they go down the path of opposition, where there person they\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92re dating starts to have larger needs, or struggling emotionally, or insecurities, they bring those problems to the partner, he may meet that with a kind of disgust and revolt\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 I am not dealing with your shit, I am not taking care of you. So as an adult, when the person brings the other their challenges, I dont\u8217\'92 know what to do with this, im struggling with x, it can cause a lot of reactivity because it feels like a threat, like he\u8217\'92s going to be put back into that position of being that person\u8217\'92s parent or caretaker. That can cause a lot of men to push relationships away. If you are in that position, it\u8217\'92s likely that you are the taker.}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 Unable to say no to her, unable to stop chasing, unable to really emotionally connect.}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 Signs of codependency}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 Low self esteem, over people pleasing, poor boundaries.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 Reactivity. Overreactivity; very high tendency of both the taker and the giver to overpersonalize things. }
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 Denial; denying that there are problems in the relationship, that the partner isn\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92t treating you well. }
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 Investing a lot of a lot of time and energy into a relationship and sacrificing your own needs wants and relationships. Investing a lot of time and energy into caring for your partner\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s dysfunction.}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 Making excuses for other person\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s bad behaviors.}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 Not allowing your partner to take responsibilities for their own lives. They bring you a problem, and you immediately try to take over solving that problem for them. You get frustrated when they don\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92t want your help. That can cause tension. Not allowing partner to maintain independence.}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 If you are the giver, your partner doesn\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92t like if you make plans with friends, or go camping, or watch the sports game. All of a sudden they\u8217\'92re making a big deal about how you don\u8217\'92t prioritise them.}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 There are levels to this. You might not be stage 5 code red codependency, but there may be some in it.}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 Ask youreelf.}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 1.) do I feel obligated or compelled to help my partner above myself.}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 2.) do I tend to over prioritize my partners needs and wants}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 3.) do I let my partner overprioritize my needs and wants above my own.}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 4.) do I on a regular basis feel ashamed of who I am?}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 5.) Do I consistently or regularly try to control the outcomes of other people when I feel helpless or guilty?}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 6.) do I have a hard time asking for help?}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 7.) do I often avoid talking about my problems in an open and honest way.}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 Co dependenet- one person is a giver, one is a taker.}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 Fixing:}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 1.) do not villanize codependent behaviors.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 \tab - its like a chinese finger trap, wanting desperately to get out tightens the trap. Shaming your behaviors enforces the codependency. Instead, contextualize behavior. They are an adaptive survival strategy. So ask yourself, \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93how did this adaptive survival strategy help me feel safe, connected, and valued, and attention.\u8221\'94 A big piece of shifting out of codependency is seeing how needy behaviors were there to help you stay safe in an unwelcome environment.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 2.) Little acts of selfishness.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 \tab - things you know you need to do in order to feel safe, independent, sovereign, and confident.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 \tab - write down a list of acts of selfishness on a daily or weekly basis}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 \tab \tab - daily workout, meditation, hanging out with friends, signing up for a hobby, learning about finances.  }
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 \tab - more robust qulity of independence}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 \tab - a secure, healthy relationship is two independent sovereign people choosing one another actively, choosing to respect their own sovereign and independent choices, and choosing to support one another in that development. Its not, im responsible for you, you\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92re responsible for me, its we\u8217\'92re resonsible for ourselves and we choose to do that together with one another.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 \tab - I need to figure myself out. I am putting this shit on blast.}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 3.) expose yourself to disappointement}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 \tab Exposure therapy.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 \tab People in codependent relationships have extremely low threshold for disappointment. The giver has low threshold for disappointing the other, and the taker has a low threshold for being disappointed by the other person. Its both people\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s responsibility to elevate and expand that level of disappointment. In a healthy secure relationship, its okay to be disappointed by your partner. I\u8217\'92m okay when she\u8217\'92s disappointed. Saying no to her wanting to go somewhere to see a show. Can be helpful to talk about with partner. Here are some specific ways about how in the past, ive been been saying yes to you, when really it was a no, I wanted to go watch a game with my buddies.}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 4.) go on a journey of discovery}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 \tab - what the hell are your needs?}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 \tab - don\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92t actually know what your needs are. }
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 \tab - I don\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92t actually know what I want or need.}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 \tab Relational needs.}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 Perfection is the fuel for codependency- both people get caught in expecting perfection. The taker will expect perfection from the giver, the giver will expect perfection from themselves. If you\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92re not perfect at understanding what I need, what I want, then its a sign and a signal that I don\u8217\'92t matter to you. Perfection is where punishment happens.  Start to look at where you and partner are starting to look at where you are competing, or keeping a tally, a battle of fairness, a scoreboard, perfectionism is right there. That fairness competition is what reinforces the codependent behavior, and gives the two of you something to argue about, fight about, and reinforces giver/taker mentality. Any times one of you is using \u8216\'91always\u8217\'92 \u8216\'91never\u8217\'92, thats a good sign you are scorekeeping. Instead, move to relational language. How do we want to approach this. How do we as a couple want to approach this?}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 5.) get to know the signs of backsliding}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 Make a bunch of progress - and then after 2-5 months, old behaviors will creep back in. You will start to deprioritize your needs, deprioritize your wants. You start to run the story in the script that the other person doesn\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92t care about what you want or need, and you will start to backslide. Get to know the signs as a couple of the signs of codependency, because one of you will be able to catch it. \u8220\'93Ive noticed that both of us as not been prioritize the little acts of selfisheness. I\u8217\'92ve noticed that I\u8217\'92ve been saying yes to things that have actually been a no for me.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 6.)Enlist someone else in the relationship to support you in letting go of this codependency. }
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1
